,Not Recommended,289930,17166273,"Posted: 21 July, 2015",all,PotatoMan,"The business aspect of the game are superficial at best - There's no competition, no global fluctuations in the market, and all you can do is carry project cargo with container ships. Seriously, you can't establish liners services or anything; you're picking up one or two cargoes at best and essentially tramping. It's really not very complex, and the campaign is just a grind. The price of tug service doesn't make sense (It's about 50 to 1000 more than they cost in real life, seriously), and neither do the ship improvements - I have to stop a ship for two days to get a license to carry dangerous goods? Not only is firefighting gear an option, it's only available on the largest ships?If you're looking for a remotely realistic simulation of the shipping business, give it a pass.The ship simulation aspect is similarly basic... No transverse thrust on the propeller, only the larger ships have bow and stern thrusters, there's no wind or current and the ships don't have inertia. Seriously, the best way to make a dock perpendicular to the direction you started with is to speed up, then turn at the last minute and slide sideways into it, Dukes of Hazard style.Give it a pass, and be very careful when considering the new version."
