76561198156301654,Not Recommended,289930,12895700,"Posted: 11 November, 2014",all,Sage Creek Kid,"If someone is willing to spend several hours, or days, working through the various levels of achievement this game has--then see it all taken away in the space of 10 to 15 seconds--and for no apparent reason--this is the game for you!  Otherwise, STAY AWAY!This game is divided into difficulties of play:  ""easy,"" ""normal,"" ""hard,"" etc.  When playing above the ""easy"" level this game can be very frustrating to play.  The experience is similiar to one playing a ""rigged"" game in the very few casinos that have them.  This game has three main characters:  the ""investor;"" the ""assistant,"" and the ""old captain.""  The assistant is, basically, a tutorial device.  The information the ""assistant"" provides is useful.  The ""old captain"" will tell you if you did something wrong in docking at a port or sailing out of one.  The ""old captain"" also provides advice on how to maintain your ships.  The ""investor"" is a very sneeky and greedy individual.  The contract you are forced to sign with her (if playing in ""normal"" status or above) is so unfair that, in real life, an American court would probably rule such a contract to be void.  Without warning this ""investor"" is allowed to demand that you ship a list of goods to a port she has selected.  If you are unable to comply with this demand this ""investor"" can throw you out of the game.  Sometimes, however, this investor will let you off with a warning.The ""normal,"" and higher, categories of this game are sub-divided into various titles--""Consignor,"" ""Ship Boss,"" etc.  The player reaches these titles after completing certain tasks.  These tasks can take up to 3 to 4 hours of playing time for each title.  The BIGGEST problem with this game is the secrecy and lack of information the developers have, either, intentionally built into the game, or, the developers have no desire to make corrections to make the game rules clearer and fairer to the player.  You can be kicked-out of this game for no apparent reason.  The worse part is this game is, obviously, designed to kick you out only after several hours of play.  You may have progressed (as I did) to the third title; have 8 to 10 ships; and have a balance of 130 million Euros.  Then, for no understandable reason, the calendar starts spinning wildly (and NOT responding to the ""pause game"" or ""slow down"" keys) and your balance, likewise, starts wildly dropping.  After about 10 to 15 seconds you get a message that your company is bankrupt--thus, you've been thrown out of the game.  Of course, you always have the option to start a new game--with no credit or assets from the game you just got thrown out of!"
